\section{Agreement with usearch}{
 This reimplementation follows the \emph{paper}.
The usearch v11 binary diverges from its own description in undocumented ways
(an absolute low-count cap of ~8 rather than \code{s*N_i/n}, the \code{X_i/N_i} rate,
and an iterative candidate selection), so the returned value is of the
\strong{same order of magnitude} as usearch's de novo estimate but is \strong{not}
bit-exact. On integer-count data the per-OTU \code{X_i/N_i} reproduces usearch's
reported rate when the same low-count set is used; the median over the whole
table does not. See \code{\link[=uncross2_pq]{uncross2_pq()}} for the score-side comparison.
